Using an in-memory token cache is suitable for single-server development scenarios. However, for production applications, especially those deployed to multiple servers, a distributed cache is necessary for scalability and reliability.

It would be helpful to add a comment to guide users of this template, for instance:

```csharp
// The following line adds an in-memory token cache. This is for development purposes.
// For production scenarios, consider using a distributed cache.
// See https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-identity-web/wiki/token-cache-serialization
.AddInMemoryTokenCaches();
```

This same consideration applies to the `.AddInMemoryTokenCaches()` call for `IndividualB2CAuth` on line 94.

Using `_httpClient.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add` can lead to an `InvalidOperationException` if `CallWebApi` is called more than once on the same `DownstreamWebApi` instance. This is because `Add` will attempt to add the 'Authorization' header again, which is not allowed.

While `DownstreamWebApi` is registered as transient, a consumer (like a controller) could be injected with an instance and call this method multiple times within a single request, causing a runtime error on the second call.

It's recommended to set the authorization header on a per-request basis using `HttpRequestMessage` to avoid modifying the shared `HttpClient` state. This is a safer and more robust approach.

Suggested change (replaces lines 55 and 58):
```csharp
using var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Get, apiUrl);
request.Headers.Authorization = new System.Net.Http.Headers.AuthenticationHeaderValue("bearer", accessToken);
var response = await _httpClient.SendAsync(request);
```

Using `request.Headers.Add()` can throw an `InvalidOperationException` if the 'Authorization' header already exists. It's more robust to set the `Authorization` property directly, which will set or replace the header.

```csharp
string accessToken = await _tokenAcquisition.GetAccessTokenForUserAsync(_initialScopes);
request.Headers.Authorization = new System.Net.Http.Headers.AuthenticationHeaderValue("Bearer", accessToken);
```

This approach is safer and also aligns with recent improvements made to the original `microsoft-identity-web` templates.

