This `Debug.Assert` is a good safeguard for development builds, but it will be compiled out in RELEASE builds. This could lead to silent failures where Kestrel incorrectly uses a development certificate instead of one specified by the user in configuration, which is a potential security risk.

Given the PR's goal to provide helpful error messages at bind-time for misconfigurations, it would be better to replace this assertion with a runtime check that throws an `InvalidOperationException`. This would prevent silent failures in production and guide the user on how to enable HTTPS configuration correctly.

For example:
```csharp
var httpsConfigurationService = ApplicationServices.GetRequiredService<IHttpsConfigurationService>();
if (!httpsConfigurationService.IsInitialized)
{
    // This can happen if 'UseKestrelSlim' is used and an HTTPS endpoint is configured without a call to 'UseHttpsConfiguration'.
    // We might incorrectly favor the development certificate over one specified by the user in configuration.
    throw new InvalidOperationException("HTTPS configuration is not initialized. To use HTTPS, call 'webBuilder.UseHttpsConfiguration()' when building the host.");
}
```

The current `if`/`else if` structure is a bit difficult to follow because the `else if` condition depends on a side effect (`out certificatePath`) from a clause within the `if` statement.

To improve readability and make the control flow more explicit, consider refactoring this method to use guard clauses. This would flatten the structure and make it easier to understand the different paths.

For example:
```csharp
private CertificateAndConfig? FindDeveloperCertificateFile(ConfigurationReader configurationReader)
{
    if (!configurationReader.Certificates.TryGetValue("Development", out var certificateConfig) ||
        certificateConfig.Path != null ||
        certificateConfig.Password == null)
    {
        return null;
    }

    if (!TryGetCertificatePath(_applicationName, out var certificatePath))
    {
        return null;
    }

    if (!File.Exists(certificatePath))
    {
        _serverLogger.FailedToLocateDevelopmentCertificateFile(certificatePath);
        return null;
    }

    try
    {
        var certificate = new X509Certificate2(certificatePath, certificateConfig.Password);

        if (IsDevelopmentCertificate(certificate))
        {
            return new CertificateAndConfig(certificate, certificateConfig);
        }
    }
    catch (CryptographicException)
    {
        _serverLogger.FailedToLoadDevelopmentCertificate(certificatePath);
    }

    return null;
}
```
This revised structure has the same logic but is more straightforward.

While this correctly asserts that an exception is thrown, the reason for failure differs based on the `useQuic` parameter. The PR description mentions that a goal of this change is to provide helpful error messages.

When `useQuic` is `false`, startup should fail because QUIC isn't enabled for an HTTP/3 endpoint. The error message should guide the user to call `UseQuic()`.
When `useQuic` is `true`, startup should fail because configuration-based HTTPS isn't automatically enabled with `UseKestrelSlim`. The error message should guide the user to call `UseHttpsConfiguration()`.

To make this test more robust and verify the user-friendly error messages, I suggest capturing the exception and asserting on its message content based on the `useQuic` flag.

A similar improvement could be made to the `UseKestrelSlim_CodeBased` test to check for specific error messages for its various failure conditions.

For example:
```csharp
var exception = Assert.Throws<InvalidOperationException>(host.Run);

if (useQuic)
{
    // This test case would pass if `UseQuic` also enabled HTTPS configuration.
    // With UseKestrelSlim, configuration-based HTTPS requires an explicit call to UseHttpsConfiguration().
    Assert.Contains("UseHttpsConfiguration", exception.Message, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
}
else
{
    // HTTP/3 requires QUIC, which is not enabled by default with UseKestrelSlim.
    Assert.Contains("UseQuic", exception.Message, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
}
```

The current order of operations, where `OnSigningIn` is set before `configureOptions` is called, allows consumers to inadvertently replace the security-critical `OnSigningIn` handler. This would disable security stamp validation on token refresh, which is a key feature of this method.

To make this more robust, I recommend calling `configureOptions` first, and then chaining the `HandleSigningIn` logic with any handler the user might have configured. This ensures the Identity logic always runs, while still allowing for user customization.

Suggested implementation:
```csharp
return builder.AddBearerToken(IdentityConstants.BearerScheme, bearerOptions =>
{
    configureOptions(bearerOptions);

    var existingOnSigningIn = bearerOptions.Events.OnSigningIn;
    bearerOptions.Events.OnSigningIn = async context =>
    {
        // Run Identity's handler first to validate stamp and refresh principal.
        await HandleSigningIn<TUser>(context);

        // If the principal is still valid, run any user-configured handler.
        if (context.Principal is not null)
        {
            await existingOnSigningIn(context);
        }
    };
});
```
This approach allows users to add custom logic that runs after the principal has been refreshed, while preventing accidental removal of the core Identity behavior.

This change removes the `HandleSigningIn<TUser>` logic, which performs security stamp validation and is the core feature of this `AddIdentityBearerToken` method. As per the issue description, this method is intended to wire up Identity-specific behavior for bearer tokens. With this change, the method no longer provides this integration.

Was this removal intentional? If you were trying to fix the issue where `configureOptions` could overwrite the `OnSigningIn` handler, a better approach is to chain the handlers instead of removing the Identity-specific one.

For example:
```csharp
return builder.AddBearerToken(IdentityConstants.BearerScheme, bearerOptions =>
{
    // Apply user configuration first.
    configureOptions(bearerOptions);

    // Then, chain our logic with any existing handler.
    var existingOnSigningIn = bearerOptions.Events.OnSigningIn;
    bearerOptions.Events.OnSigningIn = async context =>
    {
        await HandleSigningIn<TUser>(context);

        if (context.Principal is not null && existingOnSigningIn is not null)
        {
            await existingOnSigningIn(context);
        }
    };
});
```
This would restore the functionality while also making it more robust.

This implementation of `IConfigureOptions<BearerTokenOptions>.Configure` will throw a `NotImplementedException` if `BearerTokenOptions` are configured without a name (e.g., via `services.Configure<BearerTokenOptions>(...)`). This method is intended to configure the default options instance.

It should delegate to the named `Configure` overload, passing `Options.DefaultName` for the scheme name:

```csharp
public void Configure(BearerTokenOptions options)
{
    Configure(Options.DefaultName, options);
}
```

This is the standard pattern for implementing `IConfigureNamedOptions<T>` as seen in other authentication handlers in this repository (e.g., `CookieAuthenticationConfigureOptions`).

This check for `[RequiredAttribute]` only considers attributes on action method parameters directly. It doesn't account for properties of complex types that are bound from the request, for example with `[FromQuery]`. The issue description specifically mentions properties on a class/record, which this implementation doesn't seem to cover for all binding sources.

When a complex type is bound (e.g., from the query string), ApiExplorer creates an `ApiParameterDescription` for each property, and the `ParameterDescriptor` will be a `ControllerBoundPropertyDescriptor` (for MVC) or `PageBoundPropertyDescriptor` (for Razor Pages). These types expose a `PropertyInfo` that should be checked for the `[RequiredAttribute]`.

You could modify this method to handle these cases as well. A switch expression on `parameter.ParameterDescriptor` could make the implementation clean:

```csharp
private static bool IsRequired(ApiParameterDescription parameter)
{
    System.Reflection.MemberInfo? memberInfo = parameter.ParameterDescriptor switch
    {
        IParameterInfoParameterDescriptor p => p.ParameterInfo,
        Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Controllers.ControllerBoundPropertyDescriptor c => c.PropertyInfo,
        Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ApplicationModels.PageBoundPropertyDescriptor p => p.PropertyInfo,
        _ => null
    };

    var hasRequiredAttribute = memberInfo is not null &&
        memberInfo.GetCustomAttributes(inherit: true).Any(attr => attr is RequiredAttribute);

    // Per the OpenAPI specification, parameters that are sourced from the path
    // are always required, regardless of the requiredness status of the parameter.
    return parameter.Source == BindingSource.Path || parameter.IsRequired || hasRequiredAttribute;
}
```
This would require adding `using` statements for `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Controllers` and `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ApplicationModels`.

This line uses `hasRequiredAttribute`, but its calculation in the preceding lines (49-51) appears to be incorrect and should result in a compilation error.

The expression `propertyInfo.AttributeProvider?.GetCustomAttributes(inherit: false).Any(...)` attempts to call the `.Any()` extension method on a nullable `object[]?` type, which is not valid. The null-conditional operator `?.` applies only to `GetCustomAttributes`, not the subsequent `.Any()` call.

To fix this, you could introduce another null-conditional operator before `.Any()`:

```csharp
var hasRequiredAttribute = (propertyInfo.AttributeProvider?
    .GetCustomAttributes(inherit: false))?
    .Any(attr => attr is RequiredAttribute);
propertyInfo.IsRequired |= hasRequiredAttribute ?? false;
```

Alternatively, for improved clarity, you could restructure the logic:

```csharp
var attributes = propertyInfo.AttributeProvider?.GetCustomAttributes(inherit: false);
if (attributes?.Any(attr => attr is RequiredAttribute) == true)
{
    propertyInfo.IsRequired = true;
}
```
This second approach avoids the `|=` operator on a boolean and might be more readable.

For clarity and to make the test's intent more explicit, consider adding the `[FromQuery]` attribute to the parameters that are meant to be bound from the query string. While ASP.NET Core infers this correctly for simple types when no route parameter matches, being explicit improves readability and makes it clearer what's being tested, especially in conjunction with the comment on lines 353-354.

This would apply to `id`, `age`, and `guid` parameters. For example:
```csharp
builder.MapGet("/api-1", ([Required][FromQuery] string id) => { });
builder.MapGet("/api-2", ([Required][FromQuery] int? age) => { });
builder.MapGet("/api-3", ([Required][FromQuery] Guid guid) => { });
```

This line can throw an `InvalidCastException` if the type of `defaultValue` doesn't match the type described by `jsonTypeInfo`. This is a common scenario with `DefaultValueAttribute`, for example `[DefaultValue(typeof(int), "42")]` on an `int` property. Here, `defaultValue` is a string, but the serializer expects an `int`.

To make this robust, you should attempt to convert `defaultValue` to the target type before serialization. `TypeConverter` is the standard mechanism for string-based `DefaultValueAttribute` values. For other mismatches (e.g., a `long` default for an `int` property), `Convert.ChangeType` can be used.

I'd suggest replacing the body of the `ApplyDefaultValue` method with a more robust implementation that handles these conversions and avoids crashing the schema generation process on invalid input.

```csharp
if (jsonTypeInfo is null || defaultValue is null)
{
    return;
}

object? valueToSerialize = defaultValue;
var targetType = jsonTypeInfo.Type;

if (!targetType.IsInstanceOfType(valueToSerialize))
{
    try
    {
        if (valueToSerialize is string stringValue)
        {
            var converter = System.ComponentModel.TypeDescriptor.GetConverter(targetType);
            if (converter.CanConvertFrom(typeof(string)))
            {
                valueToSerialize = converter.ConvertFrom(null, System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, stringValue);
            }
        }

        if (!targetType.IsInstanceOfType(valueToSerialize))
        {
            valueToSerialize = Convert.ChangeType(valueToSerialize, targetType, System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture);
        }
    }
    catch
    {
        // Conversion failed. Do not add a default value and prevent crashing schema generation.
        return;
    }
}

try
{
    schema[OpenApiSchemaKeywords.DefaultKeyword] = JsonSerializer.SerializeToNode(valueToSerialize, jsonTypeInfo);
}
catch
{
    // Serialization can still fail in some edge cases.
    return;
}
```

