This implementation creates a temporary list via `.ToList()` on every call to `RefreshOccupancy()`. Since this method is called from several others (`Occupancy`, `IsUncoccupied`, `CanDock`, `Reserve`), some of which may be in hot paths, this can cause unnecessary GC pressure.

Furthermore, `Unreserve` performs an O(N) `Remove` operation on the list. When multiple units are removed, this can lead to poor performance.

A more efficient approach would be to use `List<T>.RemoveAll`, which modifies the list in-place without extra allocations and in O(N) time.

```csharp
public void RefreshOccupancy()
{
	reservedDockables.RemoveAll(h =>
	{
		if (h.IsAliveAndInWorld)
			return false;

		h.UnlinkProc(this);
		return true;
	});
}
```

This `while` loop results in O(N²) complexity. In each iteration, `Unreserve` is called on `reservedDockables[0]`. The `Unreserve` method calls `List<T>.Remove`, which is an O(N) operation for a list (especially removing from the start). Since the loop runs N times, the total complexity is O(N²).

This can be optimized to O(N) by iterating through the list once to call `UnlinkProc` on each item, and then clearing the list.

```csharp
void INotifyActorDisposing.Disposing(Actor self)
{
    foreach (var dockable in reservedDockables)
        dockable.UnlinkProc(this);
    reservedDockables.Clear();
}
```
