While this line correctly incorporates the environment variable into the hash, the surrounding `getInvalidationHash` function could be improved for performance and robustness.

Currently, file dependencies are hashed serially because of the `await` inside the `for...of` loop. This can be parallelized using `Promise.all` to speed up the process when many files are involved. Additionally, the `switch` statement for invalidation types is missing a `default` case, which could lead to silent errors if new types are added.

I'd suggest refactoring the entire function. Here's an example:

```javascript
export async function getInvalidationHash(
  invalidations: Array<RequestInvalidation>,
  options: ParcelOptions,
): Promise<string> {
  const sortedInvalidations = invalidations
    .slice()
    .sort((a, b) => getInvalidationId(a).localeCompare(getInvalidationId(b)));

  const hashParts = await Promise.all(
    sortedInvalidations.map(invalidation => {
      switch (invalidation.type) {
        case 'file':
          return md5FromFilePath(options.inputFS, invalidation.filePath);
        case 'env': {
          const value = options.env[invalidation.key] ?? '';
          return Promise.resolve(`${invalidation.key}:${value}`);
        }
        default:
          throw new Error(`Unknown invalidation type: ${invalidation.type}`);
      }
    }),
  );

  const hash = crypto.createHash('md5');
  for (const part of hashParts) {
    hash.update(part);
  }

  return hash.digest('hex');
}
```

This refactoring addresses the performance and robustness points. It also uses the nullish coalescing operator (`??`) and a template literal on this line for slightly better code style.

