This `match` statement is quite repetitive. Each arm for an invalid target repeats the same error creation logic. This can be refactored for better readability and maintainability.

Consider matching on the expression to get an optional error message. If the message is `Some`, an error is returned. This approach also makes it easy to provide more specific error messages for different invalid targets, which would be a great improvement over the generic "invalid assignment target". CPython, for example, provides messages like "cannot assign to literal" or "cannot assign to function call".

Here's a suggested refactoring:

```rust
pub(crate) fn assignment_target(
    target: &Expr,
) -> Result<(), LalrpopError<TextSize, Tok, LexicalError>> {
    use ruff_python_ast::Expr::*;

    let message = match target {
        // Invalid targets with specific messages
        BoolOp(_) => Some("cannot assign to boolean operation"),
        NamedExpr(_) => Some("cannot assign to assignment expression"),
        BinOp(_) => Some("cannot assign to operator"),
        UnaryOp(_) => Some("cannot assign to operator"),
        Lambda(_) => Some("cannot assign to lambda"),
        IfExp(_) => Some("cannot assign to conditional expression"),
        Dict(_) => Some("cannot assign to dict display"),
        Set(_) => Some("cannot assign to set display"),
        ListComp(_) => Some("cannot assign to list comprehension"),
        SetComp(_) => Some("cannot assign to set comprehension"),
        DictComp(_) => Some("cannot assign to dict comprehension"),
        GeneratorExp(_) => Some("cannot assign to generator expression"),
        Await(_) => Some("cannot assign to await expression"),
        Yield(_) | YieldFrom(_) => Some("cannot assign to yield expression"),
        Compare(_) => Some("cannot assign to comparison"),
        Call(_) => Some("cannot assign to function call"),
        FormattedValue(_) | FString(_) => Some("cannot assign to f-string expression"),
        StringLiteral(_) | BytesLiteral(_) | NumberLiteral(_) | BooleanLiteral(_) | NoneLiteral(_) | EllipsisLiteral(_) => {
            Some("cannot assign to literal")
        }

        // Potentially valid targets that need recursion
        Starred(e) => {
            assignment_target(&e.value)?;
            None
        }
        List(e) => {
            assignment_targets(&e.elts)?;
            None
        }
        Tuple(e) => {
            assignment_targets(&e.elts)?;
            None
        }

        // Always valid targets
        Subscript(_) | Slice(_) | Attribute(_) | Name(_) | IpyEscapeCommand(_) => None,
    };

    if let Some(message) = message {
        let error = LexicalError {
            error: LexicalErrorType::OtherError(message.to_string()),
            location: target.range().start(),
        };
        Err(LalrpopError::User { error })
    } else {
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

This structure is cleaner, less repetitive, and improves error diagnostics.

