The use of a fixed-size buffer for reading the registry value could lead to silently ignoring the policy if the list of disabled sources is too long. `RegGetValueW` will return `ERROR_MORE_DATA` if the buffer is too small, but this case is not handled, and the code will proceed as if the value doesn't exist. The comment on line 159 suggests awareness of this limitation, but for robustness, it's better to handle dynamic sizes.

To make this more robust, I recommend using the two-call pattern for `RegGetValueW`: first call it to get the required buffer size, then allocate a buffer of that size (e.g., with `std::vector<wchar_t>`), and call it again to retrieve the data.

Example:
```cpp
DWORD bufferSize = 0;
// First call to get the size. This will succeed if the value exists.
if (RegGetValueW(key, LR"(Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\Terminal)", L"DisabledProfileSources", RRF_RT_REG_MULTI_SZ, nullptr, nullptr, &bufferSize) == ERROR_SUCCESS)
{
    if (bufferSize > 0)
    {
        std::vector<wchar_t> buffer(bufferSize / sizeof(wchar_t));
        // Second call to get the data
        if (RegGetValueW(key, LR"(Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\Terminal)", L"DisabledProfileSources", RRF_RT_REG_MULTI_SZ, nullptr, buffer.data(), &bufferSize) == ERROR_SUCCESS)
        {
            // ... process buffer.data() ...
            // The rest of your loop from line 163 can go here.
        }
    }
    break; // Found the policy key, break regardless of success in reading.
}
```
This will ensure that the policy is correctly applied regardless of the length of the disabled sources list.

