Using `-1` here for a null value creates a hash collision. The 32-bit value for `-1` (`0xFFFFFFFF`) is identical to the representation of an opaque white `Windows.UI.Color` (`{A=255, R=255, G=255, B=255}`). This means a null `SelectionColor` will hash to the same value as a `SelectionColor` for opaque white.

A more robust way to handle nullable objects in a hash is to first hash a boolean indicating if the value is null.

Also, note that the `IsIndex` property is currently not being hashed for non-null values (on line 403), which will also lead to collisions. The hash should incorporate all properties that define the object's state.

I'd suggest rewriting this `hash_trait` specialization like this:
```cpp
void operator()(hasher& h, const M& value) const noexcept
{
    if (value)
    {
        h.write(false); // is not null
        h.write(value.TextColor());
        h.write(value.IsIndex());
    }
    else
    {
        h.write(true); // is null
    }
}
```

