While switching to a sequential `for...of` loop does make the connection behavior deterministic and helps mitigate the race condition that caused flaky tests, it introduces a performance regression by connecting to databases sequentially instead of in parallel. This could impact application startup time for users with multiple database connections.

Additionally, this solution doesn't fully prevent dangling connections; if a connection fails, any preceding successful connections in the loop will still be left open.

A more robust solution that preserves parallelism and ensures proper cleanup would be to wrap the original `Promise.all` in a `try...catch` block. In the `catch` block, you can then iterate over the connections that were being created and explicitly close any that successfully connected before the error occurred.

Example:
```typescript
try {
    await Promise.all(connections.map(connection => connection.connect()));
} catch (error) {
    // On failure, close any connections that were successfully opened.
    await Promise.all(
        connections.map(connection => {
            if (connection.isConnected) {
                return connection.close();
            }
            return Promise.resolve();
        }),
    );
    throw error; // re-throw the original error
}
return connections;
```
This approach correctly cleans up all newly created connections on failure, while maintaining the performance benefits of parallel connection setup.

